Journal readback: scoped reader credentials were absent in this worker shell, so
both requested/confirmed pairs exercised the existing fail-open spool at
`~/.joelclaw/spool/message-journal/`. Readback found two rows per flow; confirmed
keys were `telegram:7718912466:14541` and `slack:1784232557.988889` with exact
platform IDs in `metadata_json`.

Verification receipts:

- `bunx tsc --noEmit` — green.
- `pnpm exec tsc --noEmit -p packages/message-contract/tsconfig.json` — green.
- `pnpm exec tsc --noEmit -p packages/gateway/tsconfig.json` — green.
- `bun test packages/message-contract/__tests__ packages/gateway/src/chat-sdk/__tests__/outbound.test.ts`
  — 17 pass, 0 fail.
- `pnpm biome check packages/message-contract packages/gateway/src/chat-sdk packages/gateway/package.json`
  — green.
- `git diff --check` — green.

Fresh-context review fixes applied: Telegram policy is now mandatory, shadow
journal IDs parse the SDK composite Telegram ID, shadow compares target, missing
reply anchors get terminal rows, terminal event timestamps are honest, transport
activation requires explicit legacy-ownership transfer, schemas reject blank
identity/time fields, and SDK logs redact payload-shaped metadata.

Fresh-context re-review passed with no blocker/high finding beyond the documented
SDK reply limitation below.

Cutover stop: Chat SDK 4.34 can encode Slack `thread_ts`, but exposes no native
Telegram `reply_parameters` or Discord `message_reference` send surface. The
current v1 preserves the parent flow/conversation and does not falsely claim a
native message-reference reply on those two platforms. Steering must approve a
thin platform extension or upstream SDK change before declaring cross-platform
`replyTo` parity.

No commit, push, daemon edit/restart, channel enable, k8s publish, or old-path
rewire was performed.


## Steering close — 2026-07-16

Live-proven and closed: three contract-v2 sends delivered (Telegram
7718912466:14541 + :14542 confirmed, Slack 1784236079.731449), journal
flowId mapping read back, and one real integration gap found+fixed live:
the signal policy suppressed `message-contract/*` sources — v2 alert
(operator lane, high/critical) now speaks the policy's `notify.message`
source, everything else faces the classifier honestly. Gateway wiring:
shadow taps + exported SLACK_BOT_TOKEN in the start script; two clean
supervised restarts. Remaining canaries (reaction-on-outbound, burst,
kill-during-ingress) belong to the shadow-window/cutover step.
